Today we celebrate Juneteenth or the United States' second independence day. On June 19th, 1865- 2,000 Union troops arrived in Galveston Bay, Texas, and announced that the more than 250,000 enslaved black people in the state were free by executive decree. Join us tomorrow at the MCC Theater for the film screening of Poly Styrene: I am Cliché! 🎥 ​​​​​​​​ CUP OF CULTURE​​​​​​​​ KCSB-FM X MCC COLLABORATION - POLY STYRENE: I AM A CLICHÉ SCREENING​​​​​​​​ POLY STYRENE​​​​​​​​ WED, FEB 23, 6:00 PM PST​​​​​​​​ MCC THEATER​​​​​​​​ Poly Styrene was the first woman of colour in the UK to front a successful rock band. She introduced the world to a new sound of rebellion, using her unconventional voice to sing about identity, consumerism, postmodernism, and everything she saw unfolding in late 1970s Britain, with a rare prescience. As the frontwoman of X-Ray Spex, the Anglo-Somali punk musician was also a key inspiration for the riot grrrl and Afropunk movements. ​​​​​​​​ But the late punk maverick didn’t just leave behind an immense cultural footprint. She was survived by a daughter, Celeste Bell, who became the unwitting guardian of her mother’s legacy and her mother’s demons. Misogyny, racism, and mental illness plagued Poly’s life, while their lasting trauma scarred Celeste’s childhood and the pair’s relationship. ​​​​​​​​ Featuring unseen archive material and rare diary entries narrated by Oscar-nominee Ruth Negga, this documentary follows Celeste as she examines her mother's unopened artistic archive and traverses three continents to better understand Poly the icon and Poly the mother.​​​​​​​​ Collaboration with KCSB-FM.

Join us next Tuesday evening for Prof. Glenda Flores's lecture on Shaping the Way America' Children are Educated 📚​​​​​​​​ ​​​​​​​​ RACE MATTERS SERIES​​​​​​​​ SHAPING THE WAY AMERICA’S CHILDREN ARE EDUCATED: LATINA TEACHERS IN MAJORITY-MINORITY SCHOOLS​​​​​​​​ PROFESSOR GLENDA FLORES​​​​​​​​ TUE, FEB 22, 6:00 PM PST​​​​​​​​ ONLINE DISCUSSION​​​​​​​​ ZOOM LINK: https://ucsb.zoom.us/j/89532582564​​​​​​​​ ​​​​​​​​ Latina women make up the fastest growing non-white group entering the teaching profession at a time when it is estimated that 20% of all students nationwide now identify as Latina/o. Flores examines the complexities of being a Latina teacher in schools where the majority of parents and children are Latinx, Black and Asian. ​​​​​​​​ ​​​​​​​​ Flores is an Associate Professor of Chicano/Latino Studies at the University of California, Irvine. Her research centers on the social mobility patterns of Latinas/os into the middle class, and their workplace experiences in the white-collar world, especially teaching and medicine.

Join us next Tuesday for an online lecture with Dr. Maha Hilal as part of the Race and Religion Series! 💛 ​​​​​​​​ RACE AND RELIGION​​​​​​​​ INNOCENT UNTIL PROVEN MUSLIM: ISLAMOPHOBIA, THE WAR ON TERROR, AND THE MUSLIM EXPERIENCE SINCE 9/11​​​​​​​​ DR. MAHA HILAL​​​​​​​​ TUE, FEB 08, 6:00 PM PST​​​​​​​​ ONLINE DISCUSSION​​​​​​​​ Zoom Link: https://ucsb.zoom.us/j/82141343636​​​​​​​​ ​​​​​​​​ It's been two decades since the 9/11 attacks and the onset of the War on Terror. Addressing its catastrophic impact, Dr. Maha Hilal will share her insights on the last twenty years of the War on Terror including the role of official narrative in justifying the creation of a sprawling apparatus of state violence rooted in Islamophobia and in addition to outlining just how vast the War on Terror's apparatus is and has become. Centering the War on Terror's impact on Muslims and Muslim Americans, Dr. Hilal will also shed light on how some have internalized oppression, perpetuated collective responsibility, and how the lived experiences of Muslim Americans reflect what it means to live as part of a "suspect" community. Along the way, Dr. Hilal will reflect on what it means to dismantle and abolish the War on Terror.​​​​​​​​ Dr. Maha Hilal is an expert on institutionalized Islamophobia and has spent her career researching, writing on, and advocating and organizing against it. She is cofounder of Justice for Muslims Collective. Dr. Hilal holds a PhD in Justice, Law, and Society from American University and has received many awards, including the Department of State's Critical Language Scholarship, the Kathryn Davis Fellowship for Peace, and a Reebok Human Rights Fellowship. Her writings have been published in Al Jazeera, The Daily Beast, Vox, and US News, among others. Dr. Hilal lives in the greater Washington DC area.

On Wednesday at approximately 3:00pm, Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded to a reported structure fire in the 1700 block of W 9th St. First arriving units on scene reported smoke coming from an unattached garage located behind a single family home. Crews were able force the garage doors open to begin fighting the fire. Portions of the roof structure had already collapsed making it difficult to get to the seat of the fire but crews had it under control in approximately 20 minutes. Firefighters remained on scene to salvage and overhaul the contents of the garage to ensure the fire was extinguished. There was no damage done to any surrounding homes or vehicles. The garage was unoccupied at the time of the fire and there were no civilian or firefighter injuries reported. Sioux Falls Fire Responded with 21 firefighters, 4 fire apparatus and 3 support units. The cause of the fire is under investigation. There were no fire suppression or fire alerting systems in the garage. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue was assisted by SFPD, Metro Communications, PCLS ambulance, XCEL Energy, and MidAmerican Energy. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue would like to remind citizens to be aware of any hazards that may be present in storage areas and that you follow recommended procedures for maintaining safe distances between them. For more information from Sioux Falls Fire Rescue, visit www.siouxfalls.org/fire:=:https://www.siouxfalls.org/fire or follow us on facebook.com/siouxfallsfire and twitter.com/siouxfallsfire:=:https://twitter.com/siouxfallsfire

Structure Fire at 622 S Blauvelt Ave At 0500 Saturday morning, Sioux Falls Fire Rescue was dispatched to a report of a fire at 622 S Blauvelt Ave. The first arriving crew found a single family home with fire coming from a bedroom window. The occupants were able to exit the structure prior to emergency personnel arriving on scene. An initial report from the occupant was that everyone was out of the home. Firefighters were able to extinguish the fire from the exterior, and the interior of the structure in approximately fifteen minutes. Once the fire was brought under control, crews were able conduct a thorough search. There was significant fire damage to the bedroom, and smoke damage to the home which displaced the family for the foreseeable future. The family is being assisted by American Red Cross. There were no injuries to occupants or responders that were reported. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded with 6 fire trucks, 2 support vehicles, and 18 personnel. The cause of the fire is still under investigation. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue was assisted on scene by Sioux Falls Police Department, American Red Cross, Xcel Energy, MidAmerican Energy, and PCLS Ambulance. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue would like to remind residents to test their smoke alarms monthly, check the alarm expiration date, and also have an evacuation plan in place for your family. For more information from Sioux Falls Fire Rescue, visit www.siouxfalls.org/fire:=:https://www.siouxfalls.org/fire or follow us on facebook.com/siouxfallsfire or twitter.com/siouxfallsfire:=:https://twitter.com/siouxfallsfire

Sioux Falls Fire Rescue Announces Smoke Alarm Program Partnership with Helpline Center Sioux Falls Fire Rescue (SFFR), in partnership with the American Red Cross and Helpline Center, has announced a program to provide smoke alarms and installation free of charge to Sioux Falls residents. Smoke alarms are the first line of defense in residential fires. Residents can call 211 for questions or concerns regarding smoke alarms, which are the first line of defense in residential fires. Helpline Center staff will determine the type of service needed. Fire Rescue will respond to battery replacements, chirping smoke alarms, expired smoke alarms, and more. “Before 2005, there were a series of devastating fatal fires with a common occurrence of no working smoke alarms,” according to Fire Inspector Brandon Fey. “The smoke alarm program started in 2005, and in that year Sioux Falls Fire Rescue handed out over 7,000 smoke alarms.” The program assists in saving lives and protecting property communitywide, including non-English speaking residents. The Helpline Center staff can take calls from residents who speak languages other than English. SFFR is installing Smoke Alarm Program graphics that include translations in Spanish, Swahili, and Nepali on its vehicles.

Project NICE/KEEP 2022 Neighborhood Cleanup Each year the Sioux Falls Health Department’s Environmental team receives approximately 1,800 calls and referrals from citizens concerned about neighborhood nuisance issues. Additional City departments handling code enforcement issues also receive a significant numbers of calls regarding additional code violations. Projects NICE (Neighborhood Improvement Complaint Easement) and KEEP (Keep Environmental Enhancement Permanent) lend a helping hand in the form of a cleanup using City volunteers and provide selected neighborhoods with education materials about the City and its services. 2022’s Project NICE/KEEP neighborhood cleanup will be in operation next week, April 25–29. Property owners that are included in this year’s Projects NICE and KEEP have received mailings detailing the specifics of the cleanup. “Each year, our Environmental health team and City employee volunteers look forward to the successful execution of Projects NICE and KEEP,” said Dominic Miller, Environmental Health Manager for the City of Sioux Falls. “For over 30 years, these projects have been extremely successful in keeping our neighborhoods healthy and safe, as well as helping to maintain property values. Our goal is to provide residents fair and equitable access to these programs while simultaneously maintaining or improving the environmental conditions of neighborhoods across town.” Following the cleanup, a follow-up survey effort ensures that each participating neighborhood is reviewed for environmental concerns and the appropriate persons notified for correction. “Sioux Falls is a great place to live, work, and play,” said Dr. Charles Chima, Public Director for the City of Sioux Falls. “Projects NICE and KEEP are some of the many ways the City government partners with the community to promote and protect health and well-being in our city’s neighborhoods.” For more information, visit https://siouxfalls.org/code-enforcement/nice-keep where you will be able to track the progress of crew members during next week’s cleanup. You may also use this to see if your property is located within this year’s cleanup borders.

Structure Fire at 1709 W. 10th St. On Friday morning, April 15, 2021 at approximately 2:10 a.m., Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded to a reported structure fire at 1709 W 10th St. On dispatch, Metro Communications advised that the basement of the home was on fire. First arriving crews found heavy smoke coming from the basement and first floor of a 1 ½ story house. Crews pulled multiple 1 ¾” hose lines and made entry into the basement and first floor. A search was conducted of all floors and no occupants were found in the structure. The fire was located in the basement and extinguished in 15 minutes. Fire personnel remained on scene for several hours investigating the fire and ensuring no hot spots remained. There were no injuries reported at this incident and all occupants safely exited the home prior to SFFR arrival. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded with 6 fire trucks, 3 support vehicles, and 25 firefighters. The home did not have a sprinkler system. The fire is currently under investigation. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue was assisted on scene by Metro Communications, Sioux Falls Police Department, PCEMS Ambulance, MidAmerican Energy, and Red Cross. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue would like to remind homeowners to please test the smoke detectors in their home monthly. For more information from Sioux Falls Fire Rescue, visit www.siouxfalls.org/fire:=:https://www.siouxfalls.org/fire or follow us on facebook.com/siouxfallsfire or twitter.com/siouxfallsfire:=:https://twitter.com/siouxfallsfire.

Administrator Guzman Honors State Small Business Persons of the Year Award Winners. Top Entrepreneurs to be formally recognized on May 5 during National Small Business Week Awards Ceremony Karla Deann Santi, Blend Interactive, Inc., Sioux Falls Named SBA South Dakota Small Business Person of the Year Today, Administrator Isabella Casillas Guzman, head of the U.S. Small Business Administration (SBA) and voice for America’s 32.5 million small businesses in President Biden’s Cabinet, announced the 2022 Small Business Persons of the Year winners from each of the nation’s 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands. The winners will be formally recognized on May 5 during the National Small Business Week (NSBW) Virtual Summit’s Awards Ceremony, May 2-5. This year’s NSBW theme, “Building a Better America Through Entrepreneurship,” highlights the resilience, ingenuity, and creativity of these award winners who, like millions of small businesses, have navigated challenges from the pandemic and contributed to our nation’s economic comeback. “I am delighted to recognize our National Small Business Week winners from across the country who have stepped up to build their businesses, create jobs, and power historic recovery over the past year,” Administrator Guzman said. “Entrepreneurs are innovators and creators at their core, delivering the products and services we depend on and making our neighborhoods, towns, and cities more vibrant places to live and work. They give their all to achieve their American dream of business ownership and, by doing so, advance America’s economy and global competitiveness. Our 2022 award winners represent the vibrancy and resiliency of our nation’s 32.5 million small businesses, and I look forward to celebrating these small business giants and the positive impact they have had on lives and livelihoods in communities all across America.” National Small Business Week will be observed May 1-7, 2022. It will celebrate our small businesses, provide critical resources and recognize SBA partners for their support in providing startups and small business owners with counseling and advice, skills development, disaster preparedness and recovery, as well as access to capital, government contracting, and market opportunities to start, grow and build resilient businesses. About National Small Business Week For more than 60 years, the President of the United States has issued a proclamation announcing National Small Business Week, which recognizes the critical contributions of America’s entrepreneurs and small business owners. More than half of Americans either own or work for a small business, and they create about two out of every three new jobs in the U.S. each year. As part of National Small Business Week, the U.S. Small Business Administration takes the opportunity to highlight the impact of outstanding entrepreneurs, small business owners, and others from all 50 states and U.S. territories. Every day, they’re working to grow small businesses, create 21st century jobs, drive innovation, and increase America’s global competitiveness. To register for National Small Business Week and for other event information, visit www.sba.gov/NSBW.:=:https://www.sba.gov/NSBW.

Structure Fire 1900 block of South Duluth Ave At 4:38 pm April 3, 2022 Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded to a garage fire in the 1900 block of South Duluth Ave. First arriving units found smoke and flames coming from behind a house, and found an unattached garage and shed were on fire. There was some fire extension to a fence and tree. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue was able to quickly put the fire out and began overhaul on the garage which had collapsed due to the extensive fire damage. Crews remained on scene for several hours to check for hot spots. There were no civilian injuries and one minor firefighter injury. The cause of the fire is still under investigation. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded with 21 personnel, 5 fire apparatus, and 2 support vehicles. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue would like to thank Metro Communications, Sioux Falls Police Department, Patient Care EMS, Xcel Energy, and Midcontinent Communications for their assistance. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue would like to remind residents to maintain smoke detectors, change batteries semi-annually, and plan your escape routes. For more information from Sioux Falls Fire Rescue, visit www.siouxfalls.org/fire:=:https://www.siouxfalls.org/fire or follow us on facebook.com/siouxfallsfire and twitter.com/siouxfallsfire:=:https://twitter.com/siouxfallsfire

Absentee Voting Begins March 28 for City Election Absentee voting for the upcoming City of Sioux Falls Election will begin on Monday, March 28, 2022, at the Minnehaha County Administration Building, Second Floor, 415 North Dakota Avenue. All Sioux Falls voters may vote in-person at the Minnehaha County Administration Building from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m., Monday through Friday, as well as on Saturday, April 9, from 8 a.m. to 12 noon. In-person absentee voting ends at 5 p.m. on Monday, April 11. Voters may also request an absentee ballot be sent to them by mail by submitting an application to their County Auditor. The deadline for voter registration for the upcoming Tuesday, April 12, 2022, election is also on Monday. In order to vote in the upcoming election, you must be registered by 5 p.m. on March 28. Residents may register to vote at their County Auditor’s office, the City Finance office or the City Clerk’s office, driver’s license station, military recruitment offices, public assistance agencies providing food stamps (TANF or WIC), and the Department of Human Services offices, which provide assistance to the disabled. To check your current voter registration, download a Voter Registration Form, or to learn more about the election, click on “Voter Registration” at www.siouxfalls.org/election.:=:https://siouxfalls.org/council/city-clerk/election-information

Structure Fire at 610 W 17th Street Sioux Falls, South Dakota: On Sunday, March 20, 2022, at 11:34 PM Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded to a structure fire at 610 W 17 th Street. The first arriving company found fire coming from 2 garages and a tree. Crews attacked the fire from the exterior of the garages and had it extinguished in approximately 15 minutes. The fire was contained to mainly the exterior of the garages. The crews then checked for any fire extension and hot spots during overhaul. No civilian or firefighter injuries occurred during this incident. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded with 4 fire trucks, 3 support vehicles, and 21 personnel. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue was assisted by Metro Communications, Sioux Falls Police Department, Patient Care EMS, and Mid-American Energy. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue would remind residents to have working smoke detectors and a practiced escape plan in the event of a fire emergency.

Municipal Property Tax Refund Program Passes The Sioux Falls City Council approved an ordinance last night establishing a program to refund the municipal portion of property taxes on owner-occupied homes for low-income elderly and/or disabled individuals as defined by the Social Security Act. Who is eligible? Those 65 years or older and/or have a disability as defined by the Social Security Act are eligible for a Property Tax Refund if they have applied through Minnehaha or Lincoln County and are approved for South Dakota’s Assessment Freeze for the Elderly and Disabled program. Additional requirements including income limits, home market value, and more can be found on the City’s website here: siouxfalls.org/proptaxrefund:=:https://siouxfalls.org/proptaxrefund. How do people apply? Applications for South Dakota’s Assessment Freeze for the Elderly and Disabled program can be filed with the homeowner’s county treasurer’s office annually on or before April 1. Applicants must apply every year in order to remain eligible for a refund. How much money can people receive? The tax refund amount is 100% of the municipal property tax due up to a maximum refund of $500. The City of Sioux Falls will receive a list of qualified individuals and addresses directly from Minnehaha County and Lincoln County and will automatically issue refunds. The continuation of this program is subject to City Council approval annually by resolution. Refunds are issued the year after the homeowner qualifies for the Assessment Freeze for the Elderly and Disabled. For example, with City Council approval to continue the program, if the applicant applies by April 1, 2022, and is approved for an assessment freeze, they will receive a property tax refund in 2023. For more information, visit siouxfalls.org/proptaxrefund:=:https://siouxfalls.org/proptaxrefund or call the Finance office at 605-367-8860.

Boys & Girls Clubs of the Sioux Empire Announces Schedule for Fourth Annual Sioux Falls Winter Carnival Boys & Girls Clubs of the Sioux Empire (BGCSE) is kicking off the fourth annual Sioux Falls Winter Carnival started with First Friday Fat Tire Bike races at north Falls Park on Friday, February 4th. Events and proceeds raised from Sioux Falls Winter Carnival will benefit the Boys & Girls Clubs of the Sioux Empire’s mission to nurture, educate and enrich children and youth for lifelong success. Events over the last two years have been impacted by COVID-19. This year the signature Frost fundraising gala which normally signals the kick off to 9-days of Sioux Falls Winter Carnival has been postponed to Saturday, April 23rd to account for the spike in COVID related illness. The remaining events feature mostly outdoor activities. Sioux Falls Winter Carnival kicks off February 5th with events scheduled through February 13th. For a full list of events are details, visit www.bgcsiouxempire.org/events.:=:https://www.bgcsiouxempire.org/events. On Wednesday January 26,2022 at approximately 10:00pm, Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded to a reported structure fire in the 5400 block of N. Indiana Ave. While en route, Metro Communications notified responding fire units that there was smoke and flames visible from the rear of a home and it was believed that all occupants had evacuated safely. Upon arrival, the first arriving fire unit confirmed there was fire showing from the rear of the home. They were able to quickly knock down the flames on the exterior and enter the home to check for further fire extension. Another crew arrived to search the residence and confirmed that everyone was out of the house. Fire crews then checked for fire extension and began to overhaul and ventilate the home to make sure all fire was extinguished. Fire crews had the fire under control in approximately 20 minutes after arrival. Fire crews remained on scene for several hours to ensure the fire was extinguished. There were no reported injuries from the residents or the firefighters on scene and the fire remains under investigation. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue responded with four fire apparatus, 3 support vehicles, and 15 firefighters and 2 support personnel. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue was assisted on scene by Metro Communications, the Sioux Falls Police Department, PCLS Ambulance. XCEL Energy, Mid-American Energy and the American Red Cross. Sioux Falls Fire Rescue reminds residents to have working smoke detectors in their homes and when it is time to discard hot embers, ensure they are thoroughly cooled and moved a safe location away from any combustibles. For more information from Sioux Falls Fire Rescue, visit www.siouxfalls.org/fire:=:https://www.siouxfalls.org/fire or follow us on facebook.com/siouxfallsfire or twitter.com/siouxfallsfire:=:https://twitter.com/siouxfallsfire.

Filing Period for 2022 City Candidate Nominating Petitions Begins on January 28 Eligible Sioux Falls voters interested in running for office may begin circulating and filing nominating petitions on Friday, January 28, 2022, for the City Election. Nominating petitions may be filed for Mayor, At-Large Council Member “A”, At-Large Council Member “B”, Southeast District Council Member, and Central District Council Member. A valid nominating petition is required in order to be placed on the ballot. To be eligible for office, individuals must also be a registered Sioux Falls voter who has resided in the city (and their district if running for a district seat) for at least six months immediately prior to the date of the election. Nominating petitions for the Mayor and At-Large positions must consist of no less than 200 valid signatures; no less than 50 valid signatures are required for the district seats. Petitions must be filed at the City Clerk’s Office by 5 p.m. on Friday, February 25, 2022. The Regular City Election will be held on Tuesday, April 12, 2022, and will be combined with the Sioux Falls School District Election. A City Runoff Election, if needed, will be held on Tuesday, May 3, 2022. For more information, contact the City Clerk’s Office by phone at (605) 367-8080, in person at 235 West 10th Street, or by email at sfelections@siouxfalls.org. You can also visit us online at www.siouxfalls.org/election.:=:https://siouxfalls.org/council/city-clerk/election-information For information about Sioux Falls School Board nominating petitions, please contact the Sioux Falls School District Business Office at (605) 367-7905.

From our friends at Global LaborJustice: We invite you to join us at noon on Friday, June 17. Josua Mata, the general secretary of the Philippine national labor center SENTRO will be joining us for a lunch talk co-hosted by APALA and GLJ-ILRF to discuss the past, present, and future of the Philippine labor movement. After introductions from our hosts, Josua will discuss his experiences over thirty years of trade union activism in the Philippines. Surveying the labor movement’s recent history and future prospects, Josua will look back on the Duterte regime, with its violent anti-worker policies and rhetoric, and look forward to the upcoming presidency of Bongbong Marcos, which begins on June 30. We encourage all those interested in workers and human rights to attend to learn more about the Philippine labor movement from one of the leaders in the fight for justice for workers there. We’d be delighted if you joined us in person, at GLJ-ILRF’s D.C. office, or virtually on Zoom. Please RSVP here. In solidarity.

Understanding the importance of mental health is key when dealing with any youth’s well-being and is critical if you are working with young people in the child welfare system. This means understanding how childhood mental health struggles translate into young adulthood. Join NAMI-MN’s panel discussion with young adults of color as they speak about their mental health journeys on May 20 at 5:30pm CST. The core of the conversation is to highlight the generational gap that exists in the (mis)understandings regarding mental health. Unpacking the role of culture and environment they hope to speak to some of the resistance that exists within the community when individuals identify their distress as a mental health condition. The discussion will expand on intergenerational dialogues around mental health to begin to bridge the gap between immigrant generations. https://us02web.zoom.us/meeting/register/tZYkc-GhpjgqGdCT59lEr90FkbLWWRTTKsVQ

Roxane Gay is a writer, professor, editor, and social commentator whose New York Times best-selling essay collection Bad Feminist, made waves by taking a raw look at race, class, pop culture, and the state of feminism today. Through her writing, she provides her readers with an honest analysis of today’s feminist culture, while also providing an inspiring call-to-action on how we can still do better for each other today. As a writer her work pulls builds upon the legendary Black women like Audre Lorde who came before her; ensuring their legacy remains while also curating herself as one of the fiercest #BlackFeminist voices of today. Outside of writing, Roxanne Gay’s work and nuanced social commentary continuously critiques existing inequalities and builds space for the possibilities for Black people, women, and the LGBTQA+ community. We are grateful to Roxanne Gay for carrying the torch her foremothers forged, while continuing to challenge us all to humanize the flaws within modern social justice movements and inspiring us to be better allies and conspirators. #BlackHerstoryMonth #BlackFeminists #BHM2022 YWCA USA

January is #HumanTraffickingAwarenessMonth Human Trafficking can be ANYWHERE! - Rural and urban areas - Factories - Farms/ranches - Restaurants/bars - Construction sites - Hotels - Private homes Traffickers are not always strangers – in many cases, traffickers are someone the victim knows: - Family members, partners, friends, community members A Few Identifying Signs of Human Trafficking: - Signs of physical and/or sexual abuse - Fearful, anxious, depressed, tense, nervous, malnourished - Lack of knowledge of whereabouts - Claims to be “just visiting” or “passing through” with no tangible address/doesn’t know where they are staying - Fearful or anxious when Law Enforcement is discussed If you are in need of resources on Human Trafficking, some are located on the last slide of the post. Survivors of Human Trafficking can contact Legal Aid for assistance with legal matters pertaining to their victimization (i.e. protection orders, housing, custody/divorce assistance). Statewide AccessLine: 1-800-250-2016

Happy Friday! Here’s some extra inspiration to get you through the day from the endlessly inspiring Shirley Chisholm! Shirley Anita Chisholm solidified her place in history as the first African-American woman elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in 1968, and was the first woman of any race to run for President in 1972. Born to a Guyanese father and Barbadian mother in the heart of Brooklyn, Shirley Chisholm dedicated her life to improving opportunities for inner-city residents in the realms of education, workers rights, healthcare, and stood to fight for women's rights and civil rights as interconnected movements. Her campaign slogan “Unbought and Unbossed” reflects the energy and the essence of her impact in both American politics and Black American activism during a time when a woman's voice was underrepresented in both. Shirley Chisholm’s legacy is extraordinary, and we highly encourage you to learn more about her by clicking the link below: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gyEy_RRIEhE . . . #YELLS #YELLSFamily #AfterschoolProgram #ASP #CommunityActionCafe #CAC #Mentoring #BlackHistoryMonth #BlackHistory #February #Representation #Community #Empowerment #Learning #Leading #Serving #FranklinGateway #Marietta #GA

During Women’s History Month, we’re honoring women who have had significant impacts on lung health! Meet Dr. Susan La Flesche Picotte, the first Native American to graduate with a medical degree. #freecontent A new cold weather shelter will be available in North Port Saturday and Sunday, at the 100 Church, located at 14525 Tamiami Trail, Sarasota County Emergency Services staff has announced. The shelter will open at 5 p.m. on Saturday, Jan. 29, and Sunday, Jan. 30, and close the following mornings. Emergency Management officials also remind residents that pets should not be left outside during the cold weather. Anyone who needs to be outside overnight or during the early morning hours is encouraged to dress in several warm layers and limit skin exposure to the wind. Additionally, Sarasota County Fire Department officials advise the public to use caution when heating their homes, as the risk of fire and carbon monoxide poisoning increase during very cold weather due to the improper use of heating devices, so extreme caution is advised.

A few storms capable of producing small hail and gusty winds are pushing into Holt County. These could also bring welcome rain to portions of western Siouxland as they move through over the next couple of hours. I'll have the latest on News 4 at Noon, and sooner if warranted.

Everyone has a temperature warmer than yesterday morning but it is even warmer in southwestern Siouxland due to the influence of a warm front. There will be more of a breeze today and more cloud cover overhead but temps will stay mild. More on what to expect now on News 4 Today.

The next round of t-storms becomes possible around 8 PM with the peak window for strong storms through 2 AM. Areas along and west of Highway 81 (like O'Neill, Niobrara, Norfolk & Yankton) have the highest chance for storms with hail and strong winds. The latest on News 4 at Noon.

Still tracking some storms as we approach 6 AM. A severe storm in eastern Osceola/western Dickinson is moving quickly to the northeast with quarter-sized hail possible. Another storm in Harrison/Shelby Counties is not severe but capable of gusts/hail as it moves northeast.
Congratulations Dr Priyanka Dahal for splendid performance in MEC MD/MS Common Entrance Examination 2078. Online PG Nepal would like to wish you more success in your career ahead. Best wishes.

3:50 AM Radar: There is a smattering of t-storms out there. Everything in Siouxland proper has stayed below severe criteria so far but a couple of storms just to our south are. A Severe T-Storm Watch is in effect along the 275 corridor (Norfolk, Pilger, West Point) through 6 AM.

Be aware that, where the snow accumulated some yesterday in eastern Siouxland, the wind is picking it up and drifting it over the road. If you are driving areas like Highway 71, Highway 4 or Highway 7 over the next few hours, be prepared for some patchy slick spots.

The combination of temperatures in the 20s and winds that have picked up into the 15-25 mph range are giving us wind chills as low as the single digits. Bundle up before you step outside! We look at how much it will feel like spring this week now on News 4 Today.

It's another day with a high fire risk in western Siouxland. A Red Flag Warning is in effect along and west of Highway 81 this afternoon and evening. Avoid starting any fires today, either on purpose or accidentally, as those could spread quickly if they do.

Partial coverage of slush with some icy spots are being reported in much of northwest Iowa and into Cuming, Thurston and Burt Counties in northeast Nebraska. Those roads are shaded in blue on this graphic. Take it slow this morning!

The same system that gives us rain and snow showers today is bringing another threat for severe weather in the Deep South, where all modes of severe weather are possible. These are some of the same areas that have been hammered numerous times lately with strong storms.
A Severe T-Storm Watch has been issued until 11 pm for central and southern Siouxland, including Sioux City.

It's a bit chilly out there this morning after seeing some clearing overnight. Clouds are starting to move in and they will dominate the morning before we get some sunshine in the afternoon. More details on how our day plays out right now on News 4 Today!

At noon we are already seeing several gusts over 50 mph! There will likely be several more this afternoon too. Obviously, this is a day to avoid starting fires of any kind (on purpose or accidentally). Several counties do still have a burn ban, including Woodbury.
Dan Sullivan is such a juvenile embarrassment to our district. #FireDanSullivan #VoteChenoaSummers

A Fire Weather Watch is in place for much of Siouxland Friday afternoon and evening. Despite the nice rain that many of us received this week, it is still dry and northwest winds gusting up to 50 mph Friday will result in any fires that do start spreading quickly.
Some fog has formed in northeastern Siouxland this morning. Watch for some low visibility if you will be driving around Lake Park, Estherville, Emmetsburg or Estherville over the next few hours.
Here are the visibility readings just after 6 AM. You can see that many of us are at a quarter of a mile or less. Coverage continues now on News 4 Today!

Most of us are pretty quiet as we start off the day but signs of what is to come for the rest of the day are showing in O'Neill. Get ready for a blustery day with less warming as a cold front moves through the area.

Tomorrow is a day to be weather aware, especially in northwest Iowa with severe thunderstorms possible in the afternoon hours. Wind and hail are the main threats but a spin-up tornado is possible. We dig into the details in a few moments on News 4 at Noon.

You can tell that a front is moving through Siouxland this afternoon. Temperatures range from the upper 30s to the upper 70s as we approach 4 PM! That front will be bringing changes to our weather over the next 24 hours, including some light snow for northern Siouxland tonight.

Most of today will be cloudy and breezy with more typical February temperatures. However, some light precipitation becomes possible late this afternoon into the evening in the form of freezing drizzle and light snow. More on that and the incoming cold now on News 4 Today.

Temperatures are in the single digits to teens this morning and, with yesterday's north wind still in place, it is downright chilly as we start the day with wind chills below zero. There will be some improvement this afternoon but it does still stay cool this afternoon. More now on News 4 Today!

With winds gusting over 50 miles per hour at times, a Wind Advisory has been issued from Sioux City north and east. Most of this area has the advisory through 3 PM while the eastern tier of counties lasts until 6 PM. More on the wind and colder temperatures on News 4 at Noon!

Temperatures are the warmest they are going to be today early this morning. They will drop for the rest of the day and I do think we could get some areas of refreeze on roadways. Something to keep in mind as we head toward the morning commute. More now on News 4 Today!
Update!! 4 out of the 5 Gubernatorial Candidates will be at this debate! We look forward to seeing you tonight!

Just how dry has our start to 2022 been? Here are all of the days with measurable precipitation in Sioux City heading into today. Yes, there are only four of them and three of them had just one hundredth of an inch! We stand at -0.77" compared to average through February 9th.

It's a pretty mild start to our day with temperatures sitting above our average highs! We will sort of stall out over the rest of the day so we will not end up as warm as yesterday, but it will still be pretty warm for this point in February. More now on News 4 Today.

There's a pretty decent range of temperatures in Siouxland as we start off our Monday, with single digits in the far east and temps near the freezing mark in the west. We will all be seeing a pretty mild February day, though, not too unlike our Saturday! More now on News 4 Today.

Almost everyone has a temperature that is below zero this morning and wind chills are in the teens to 20s below zero. Bundle up this morning! There will be plenty of sunshine for most of the day with winds getting lighter but it stays chilly. More now on News 4 Today.

Temperatures are mostly in the single digits this morning with wind chills below zero due to a northerly breeze. With plenty of cloud cover and that breeze staying in place, it will be staying pretty chilly through the day too. More on how the day plays out now on News 4 Today.

One cold front moved through overnight and it has stirred up some pretty breezy northwest winds. A second one is moving through now and will result in our temperatures staying pretty steady in the low 30s through the day. More on how the day plays out now on News 4 Today.

It is frigid in eastern Siouxland this morning with temps dipping into the teens below zero. Meanwhile, our temps are actually rising in the west on the back of an increasing southerly wind. That will eventually all of us as the day goes along. More details now on News 4 Today.

Here's what it feels like out there as we start off our Wednesday with temperatures in the single digits to low teens and gusty northwest winds in place. It will be a jarringly colder day as we struggle to warm up at all and keep the winds going. More chilly details now on News 4 Today!
Here are our noon hour temperatures. This is where I would say that we have warmed up, but we haven't really all that much. Some of us have at least made to zero though!

Mazie Hirono is the first female senator from Hawaii and the first Asian-born immigrant elected to that post. She’s also the first Buddhist to be elected to the Senate. That’s a lot of firsts. And a lot of inspiration. Senator Hirono is known for her support and swift action on gender-based violence issues, hate crimes, and healthcare advocacy. We are #BetterBecauseOfHer.

What can we say about Stacey Abrams that hasn’t already been said thousands of times before? That, as a member of the Georgia House of Representatives from 2007 to 2017, Abrams made a name for herself as a fierce advocate for human rights; that she emerged not only as one of our most effective, galvanizing leaders, but as one of the most deeply inspirational women working today; that she made history by becoming the first woman and first Black woman to hold positions in both state and national politics? That we are, indisputably, #BetterBecauseOfHer?

Meet Kimberle Crenshaw, a pioneering civil rights advocate, professor, and leading critical race theory scholar known for not only working at the intersection of race and gender, but for coining the term #intersectionality to call attention to how systems of oppression overlap to create distinct experiences for those with multiple identity categories. Among her many contributions is co-founding and founding and leading African American Policy Forum, an intersectional think tank behind campaigns such as #SayHerName, which calls attention to police violence against Black women and girls. #BlackHerstoryMonth #BlackHistoryMonth #BHM2022

One of the factors that our April DEI Moment has been trying to point out is that many factors impact the health of underserved communities. During #BlackMaternalHealthWeek , HUD announced that it now recognizes the cause/effect of housing and health. For the first time in history, the #HUDStrategicPlan prioritizes housing to improve maternal health outcomes — because housing *is* health care. The White House even went so far as to say "The inequities that Black mothers face are not isolated incidents but, rather, the byproduct of systemic racism in our society that has festered for far too long. To root it out, and improve health outcomes, we must address a broad range of areas where unequal access persists along racial lines — including access to health care, adequate nutrition and housing, toxin-free environments, high-paying job sectors that provide paid leave, and workplaces free from harassment and discrimination.", in an official press release.

The Census Bureau's analysis given in the America Counts: Stories Behind the Numbers / What Methods Did People Use to Vote in the 2020 Election? let us peek at how people approached voting during a pandemic. The degree to which voters used nontraditional methods in the 2020 election varied across demographic groups by age, education, sex, and race/ethnicity. A larger share of voters age 65 and over voted nontraditionally (77.7%) than those in younger age groups (69.7% or less). Those with a bachelor's degree or higher also voted early or by mail at a higher rate (74.5%) than those with lower educational attainment (63.2% for high school graduates). Women (71.2%) used nontraditional voting methods higher than men (67.4%). The highest share of nontraditional voting among the racial groups was among Asian alone, non-Hispanic voters (82.4%). https://bit.ly/3E9zifi:=:https://www.census.gov/library/stories/2021/04/what-methods-did-people-use-to-vote-in-2020-election.html

The National Conference on Citizenship (NCoC) developed the Pandemic to Prosperity series using the Census Bureau's 2020 data. This is an organization that works with the Kansas Alliance for Health, Estimates of monthly poverty rates during the pandemic highlight the benefit of annual Child Tax Credit (CTC) and Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC) payments for children and working-age adults. They also illustrate how stimulus and expanded unemployment payments reduced financial hardships, particularly for children. But these payments were sporadic, such that the child poverty rate increased to above pre-pandemic levels throughout the latter half of 2020. The 2021 American Rescue Plan includes new monthly CTC payments starting in July 2021. CTC payments reduced child poverty to 11.9% in July and 11.5% in August. CTC payments will continue through December 2021. Social Security, by far the most prominent American safety net program, was enacted after the Great Depression to stabilize the financial well-being of the elderly. But the program excluded initially domestic and agricultural workers — a large share of whom were Black. Unemployment insurance and Aid to Families with Dependent Children (commonly called "welfare") programs were enacted in 1935. Programs designed to provide assistance to non-elderly low-income Americans, including Head Start, food assistance programs, and the EITC, were instituted in the 1960s and 70s. Welfare was reformed in 1996 to include work requirements, but CTC provided some support to families with children starting in 1998 regardless of work status. For 20 years, the CTC received strong bipartisan support and was increased several times, most recently in 2018. Studies of CTC's impact found that this financial support for children helped increase student test scores, reduce teen birth rates, and yield higher earnings in adulthood. In 2019, $1 trillion was spent on Social Security. In contrast, $360 billion was spent on safety net programs such as the EITC, CTC, unemployment insurance, food assistance, and child care. Still, these later programs reduce the poverty rate from 26% in 1967 to 14% by 2017 (once all such transfers are included). Other things you might want to read. U.S. Conquest of the Philippines 1899-1902 On March 6, 1906, U.S. troops massacred at least 600 men, women and children in the battle of Bud Dajo in the Philippines. Corpses were piled five deep, and many of the bodies were wounded multiple times. This crime came 8 years after the United States declared war against Spain in April 1898, launching the Spanish-American war. In August 1898, Spain, facing defeat, allowed U.S. forces to take control of Manila. By the end of 1898, Spain was forced to cede its colonies of Cuba, Guam and Puerto Rico to the U.S., and for $20 million, the Philippines. In early 1899, when it became clear the U.S. had no intention of allowing the Philippines to be independent, Emilio Aguinaldo, who led the Filipino people’s revolt against the Spanish colonialists, launched a new war of independence against the U.S. imperialists. The U.S. war on and occupation of the Philippines lasted from 1899 to 1902. More than 126,000 U.S. troops were sent to crush the Filipino people’s mass uprising, and they waged war on wide swaths of the Philippine population as a whole. According to one account: “it became commonplace for entire villages to be burned and whole populations to be imprisoned in concentration camps. No mercy was accorded to Filipino prisoners, a large number of whom were shot.” The U.S. occupiers tortured Filipino rebels, suppressed organizations of workers and peasants, burned crops and food supplies, and carried out mass executions, often by clubbing or bayoneting people to death. Filipinos who refused to pledge allegiance to the U.S. flag were sometimes imprisoned. There was a conscious U.S. policy of massacres coming from the top. In 1901, American troops retaliated against the defeat of a U.S. garrison on the island of Samar by killing all males over 10 years old, and butchering many women and children as well. An American marine major reported: “General [Jacob] Smith instructed me to kill and burn, and that the more I killed and burned the better pleased he would be; that it was no time to take prisoners, and that I was to make Samar Island a howling wilderness.” When the major asked what the age limit should be for the killing, the general said, “Everything over ten.” It is estimated that between 250,000 and one million Filipinos were killed in this U.S. war of conquest—in combat and through disease and famine. The savagery of the U.S. war was captured in pictures of American soldiers standing on mounds of the skulls and bones of Filipinos they had massacred, piled in mass graves. Torture carried out by the U.S. military included waterboarding. U.S. Lieutenant Grover Flint described how he waterboarded 160 people, and only 26 survived: “A man is thrown down on his back and three or four men sit or stand on his arms and legs and hold him down; and either a gun barrel or a rifle barrel or a carbine barrel or a stick ... is simply thrust into his jaws and his jaws are thrust back.... In the case of very old men I have seen their teeth fall out.... He is simply held down and then water is poured onto his face down his throat and nose from a jar; and that is kept up until the man gives some sign or becomes unconscious. And, when he becomes unconscious, he is simply rolled aside and he is allowed to come to.... A man suffers tremendously, there is no doubt about it. His sufferings must be that of a man who is drowning, but cannot drown....” The author Mark Twain summed up that in the Philippines, the U.S. had “buried them; destroyed their fields, burned their villages, and turned their widows and orphans out of doors; furnished heartbreak by exile to some dozens of disagreeable patriots; subjugated the remaining tens of millions....” The U.S. military carried out the conquest and “pacification” of the Filipino people under the same racist thinking and justification as their genocidal wars against Native Americans, with U.S. forces referring to the Filipinos as “niggers,” “barbarians,” and “savages.” The Spanish-American War and the U.S. conquest of the Philippines marked the bloody rise of U.S. imperialism. The U.S. rushed to take control of Spain’s colonies to prevent other rivals from grabbing them. Seizing the Philippines was a critical step in forging the American empire, because it’s a gateway to and outpost in Asia, a country with people to exploit and resources to plunder. For more on this American Crime, including sources: https://revcom.us/a/512/american-crime-58-us-conquest-of-the-philippines-en.html:=:https://revcom.us/en/a/512/american-crime-58-us-conquest-of-the-philippines-en.html *** Follow: @TheRevcoms Read: www.revcom.us:=:https://revcom.us/en Watch: YouTube.com/TheRevcoms:=:https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCBHaevn-06RSuh3k9LkA2BA

As we continue our celebration of Black History Month, we want to spotlight our leaders in Diversity, Equity and Inclusion within Dayton Children's hospital! Dayton Children's has created the Black Employee Resource Group (BERG), which is a voluntary, employee-led group whose aim is to foster a diverse, inclusive workplace aligned with Dayton Children's mission and values. The BERG currently has nearly 400 members who meet monthly to discuss their lived experiences, build their network and become familiar with the internal resources and activities throughout Dayton Children's. MeKayla Pullins is a certified community health worker as well as the vice-chair of the BERG at Dayton Children's. She says about Black History, "Black history to me, is recognizing the amazing things that our ancestors have set up for generations and generations to come. It's a reminder of why I am so proud of my Blackness and our community, and it's motivation for me to continue to strive for greatness, continue to have hope and pursue opportunities for my future. I love my dark brown skin, my tight coiled hair! It's not always easy being an African-American in this society, yet here we are, not giving up, and continuing to strive for unity and love in our communities, every single day!" It is leaders like MeKayla who help Dayton Children's achieve their core value of equity both within the hospital walls and outside in the community!
